The Slow Seed
Mira's grandfather had a saying: "The axe that falls today was sharpened yesterday." She never understood it until the summer she tried to grow a garden on the rocky patch behind their house.
Everyone told her it was a waste of time. The soil was thin, laced with stones, and the neighbors' gardens — planted in richer earth — were already green by the time she'd cleared her first row. She spent whole afternoons pulling rocks the size of fists from the ground, her palms blistering, her back aching by sundown.
Her brother Teo would lean against the fence and laugh. "You could've planted in the yard like normal people."
"This is the yard I have," she said, and kept digging.
Weeks passed. She hauled compost from the kitchen scraps, turned the soil until her arms shook, and planted rows of beans and squash long after the other gardens had already begun to flower. Nothing came up for what felt like forever. She watered anyway. She weeded anyway. Some mornings she stood over the bare dirt and wondered if she was only proving her brother right.
Then, in the second week of July, a single green shoot broke the surface — crooked, stubborn, alive. Within days there were dozens more, pushing up through soil that had once been nothing but stone.
By August, Mira's garden had outgrown every other one on the street. The beans climbed higher, the squash grew fatter, because the roots beneath them had been forced to dig deep for what they needed. What looked like the worst plot of land had become, through sheer persistence, the richest.
Her grandfather came to see it on a Sunday evening. He didn't say much — just crouched down, pressed his hand into the dark, crumbled earth, and nodded once.
"The soil doesn't care how hard the work was," he said. "Only that it was done."
Mira wiped the sweat from her brow and looked at the rows she'd built stone by stone, hour by hour. She understood the saying now. It was never about the axe, or the tree, or even the garden.
It was about showing up, day after day, long before anyone could see what you were building
